Hello - I thought I had scheduled a recall visit with the BelAir MD Genesis/Hyundia dealership/shop for today at 730am with Genesis Customer Care a week or more ago - and upon arrival this morning at the BelAir location I was told there was NO reservation under my name.  Additionally, the Genesis Customer Care representative I spoke with then indicated that the time allocated for the 2 recall repairs/replcaements would be ~2-3 hours, though this morning the BelAir technician-service lead said the time needed to allocate is closer to 6 hours!  So mis-information and no scheduling.  To add, after leaving the BelAir MD location - after being told I had no reservation - I called Genesis Customer Care @820am this morning - and the lady helping was nice on the phone yet indicated that she apologized for the scheduling inconvenience, and would be emailing me with available times to go to another Genesis dealer (Owings Mills MD) - and I am still waiting for scheduling options to be emailed to me (currently 440pm EST).  I was also told by the BelAir MD technician-service lead that the recall work I need to have done for my car could be done at any other location - which is different from what the 1st Genesis Customer Care lady told me last week or the prior week.  I am increasingly questioning what is the value of the Genesis Customer Care department 
Sincerely, Chris Haley

I'm over all happy with corporates service.  The initial conversation was pleasant and painless. I did not receive the follow up as to what was happening, but i did get an email from Vancouver Genesis saying my appointment was still scheduled for the 5th of July at 9am. However they again called and rescheduled for August 15th now. I have a feeling this will be rescheduled again, for the 4th appointment. This is no fault of corporate, but i have no idea how i could recommend the brand to anyone else given my location and the treatment our only local dealership provides. Again, no fault of Genesis itself.  It shouldn't take 3 appointments and 3 months  to have a recall service done, and the amount of stress they are causing by declining services, and rescheduling is absolutely appalling.   

I appreciate you, and i don't know if writing a complaint here will even matter. You guys tried, but unfortunately for me that dealership and the manager of their valet service is not ran by you.  If they had even a fraction of the customer service skills you guys do at your corporate office things would be entirely different. 

Your service is a 10/10
Their service is a 0/10
So the end result is i'm still incredibly unhappy, but at no fault of yours.

column14: I've yet to receive a follow up on my concern which was about the amount of time it was taking to get an appointment with a Genesis dealership for service, particularly if I'd like to use the valet service (a service is heavily advertised and that contributed to my decision to choose a Genesis over similar luxury brands). the wait for a service appointment with valet and loaner was estimated to be three months later at one dealership. When I did have a service appointment, they weren't able to check in on a few of my concerns because of how busy they were, they told me I'd have to schedule a different appointment to check those issues and I had to choose which one concerned me the most. The issue I'm needing service on is the eLSD on my GV70 returning a warning on the dash. It was investigated and a part was ordered. The part was backordered with an estimate of 4 weeks. When that new part was installed, it was also faulty and now I have an estimated 2-3 weeks for the same part. While I understand supply issues based on similar stories from Genesis owners issues and delays with this part go back over 2 years, it seems as though Genesis corporate has not taken measures to address this issue appropriately. It is bad enough there is an issue like this on a car with under 4000 miles and purchased 6 months ago but the issue in compounded greatly when the dealership experience and expectations of owning a luxury product are not being met. I love my car and think the car itself is an amazing product but the overall Genesis ownership experience is leaving a lot to be desired.

Perfect timing for me to release my frustration with Genesis.   I bought a CPO GV80 with 5K miles on it from a dealership in Southern CA, I came back to the Bay Area  after adding on 3K.  My idea was to get the courtesy oil change at the San Bruno service center. The following listed all of the issues encounterd:-
1. Called svc center, left messages and NO ONE ever called back
2. Called parts, the voice mail was FULL; I couldn't leave any message
3. Called front desk to hand deliver the call back message; NO ONE called!!
4. Called Genesis connect to inquire for oil change, the gentleman there said my car wasn't eligable for the courtesy oil change!!!  What is the world was going on!! I then called again, a lady there was nice enough to do some research and told me that the vehicle I have indeed entitle for the service.  Excellent!! However, I had to to submit a CVP request.  OK.  I followed her instructions and have akl the required documents submitted.  It has been a week already, yet, I still haven't heard from anyone!!!!

Please don't hesitate to call me at 650-255-0943  as the above was only a small portion of the story
Thx

column14:
My experience with Nicholas was really good, so I want to clarify that I rated the time it took to handle my questions as "average" only because it took about an hour on the phone with him to reset my car's connection to Connected Services and reset everything so that the app on my phone worked.  We had to go through various things on the menu, and the amount of time shouldn't be a negative reflection on Nicholas.  He was very helpful, and I had a lot of questions.
Regarding how likely I would be to recommend the Genesis brand, I have to tell you that I'm very much on the fence about this.   The car is great, and I've told people so, but I've also told them that my experiences getting the car serviced twice (once for warranty replacement of the differential and once for a regular "first service" of tire rotation and oil change) were both sub-par.   This refers specifically to Delray Genesis in Delray Beach, FL. 
I have been extremely dis-satisfied with Delray's level of professionalism, speed of work (4 days for a tire rotation and oil change), lack of willingness to offer next-level customer service (such as software update that I instead had to do myself), inputting incorrect mileage figure into service record (and failure to correct it when I notified them), failure to reset car's service interval reminder, and failure to wash the car before returning it to me.  Also, they don't answer the phone- I had to drive over there to find out why they still hadn't finished my "first service" after 4 days.  I realize that everyone is short of skilled help, but all I can tell you is that my other car is a Lexus, and the service experience there is far, far superior.   Genesis will not succeed as a brand until the dealership and service experience are on a par with other luxury brands.
My experience buying the car at Genesis Cherry Hill in Marlton, NJ was very positive, but unfortunately that's too far from where I live to get it serviced there.

column14: You asked, so here you go. It was QUITE a TERRIBLE experience (NOT due to Jessica). I called in a few weeks before my appointment to be sure the dealership had a tire I needed to replace (It had a bubbled sidewall after only 15KMi). I was told they did, that they had two actually, and that they could do my servicing & a grease & oil and fix a rocker panel and it could all be done in the AM. I was also told (both by a "Craig"), that I had the extended warrantee so the costs for the tire would be under $50.  The dealer did NOT have the tire, the warrantee expired a month earlier (but the bubble was clearly there earlier). I've asked the Dealership to honor the warrantee (still TBD). I also provided  the phone number & name of the owner of J&K Tire in Hudson, MA (where they said they could certainly match their lower price - worst case (again,  still TBD). I didn't get my car back until 8.5 Hrs after I brought it in which significantly impacted two proposals I was working on. I was VERY disappointed in the dealership, and I'm waiting to see if they do the right thing on this. PS.. Craig had  quit the dealership the week before my appointment; but, regardless, it was clear why I was coming in to have work done & the tire changed, but no one thought ahead and it cost me a day I didn't have to waste.  I'm the Chief Engineer of a portion of a large $6B-US 20K-person company and deal with many companies/vendors. I  am very disappointed with Genesis. I still haven't decided if I'm going to relate this truthful experience to the world at large on Social Media. The ball is currently in the Framingham new dealership's hands (James Thorp & Noah Whipple). If you need further information feel free to ask (my Cell is 626/833-2715). Mark Kahan

column14:
This is the third time my brand new GV70 bought from Kearny Mesa Genesis and currently with about 500 total miles has been in the shop. The second time it was in for over a week and returned to late causing me to reschedule  business appointments. This time it is projected to be out of use for five days. 

The prevalent pass-the-buck, responsibility-dodging attitude among middle management at this dealership has clearly been languishing for a very long time and has become internally acceptable but dire for investors.

My powertrain warning light came on again and Chadd Clowes, Sales Manager, told me not to drive it and not to bring it to Genesis Kearny Mesa where I bought it, but to take my car thirty miles away to the Genesis Escondido Service Department. 

Joe Spurrier, General Manager, told me he would not give me a loaner and would not rent me a car. Finally he agreed to buy me a Lyft ride home … then I could walk. 

This is a brand new car that I bought in early June at this dealership. There is a core of illness of arrogance and irresponsibility among middle management at this Kearny Mesa Dealership. There is full focus on sales for instant gratification but perhaps ultimate business failure. There appears to be virtually no emphasis on responsible follow through which of course would help secure long term success.

It is time for the SunRoad owners and Genesis Headquarters to get onsite and do some heavy duty weeding.

A footnote: perhaps GM Joe rethought his knee jerk dodge as smiley faces eventually came out of the woodwork to help and provide a loaner. But at that juncture I had endured a couple hours of unnecessary denial and abuse only to achieve what I had been promised by the same folks when I bought the car.

column14:
I did not talk to anybody named Dustin.  I did talk to two females who were unfailingly polite, courteous and as helpful as possible.  MY concern was with the navigation system.  I was promised that the situation would be looked into.  It was not resolved.  Specifically, there is no option to avoid major highways.  That is a problem in Atlanta where I live and the interstate is always under construction and I frequently want to stay on surface streets.  I also find the fact that you can't view a turn by turn menu until you start driving not only dumb, but dangerous.  The fact that you can't go through each proposed route step by step in advance makes it very difficult to decide which route to choose.   I have put a Garmin GPS in my car and will use that until these issues are resolved.  I have another issue which I did not mention and that is the requirement to confirm every time you start the car.  I have only owned my G80 less than two months and this has already frozen on me once.  The only way I could get out of this was to reset everything which meant I had to go through the entire setup process a second time.  I find this requirement incredibly annoying and inconvenient.  Having said all that, I will say that I like everything else about the car. I like the way it drives.  I like all the safety features, especially the blind spot camera which is the main reason I bought the car.
Sincerely,
John Miller
G80 owner

column14: I called to set up an appointment for my new 2023 Genesis G70 because the back turn signal isn’t working. The car is also almost due for the first oil change. I asked about using the valet service that I heard all about during the sale of the car. I was told the earliest they had that available was September 28. That was two months out. So, I explained that the turn signal wasn’t working and that I needed an appointment sooner and that I would bring the car in myself but that I had been told that they offered loaner cars while the cars were being fixed. They told me that the loaner cars were all taken and that they didn’t see any becoming available in the near future, but to go ahead and bring the car in for the oil change and the turn light. I think the free oil changes is a nice “perk” and frankly would have been impressed with just that, but why sell “extra” perks that really aren’t available? Also, I am a bit concerned that I’ve had the car 5 months and something is already not working. My previous car was an Acura and it had no problems, seriously none beyond normal wear and tear. We took a chance on Genesis and I really hope it wasn’t a costly mistake!

column14:
This comment has nothing to do with the customer service representative I spoke with on the phone. She was professional, polite and very helpful. It is however a complaint regarding customer service at the only dealership near me. 

Richmond, VA is desperately in need of another warranty center. The service department at the Genesis dealership on Midlothian Turnpike, the only option available to us, is not a place I would recommend to anyone!!  The male service manager at the dealership is horrible. The female service manager is very nice, but I believe the man I am referring to is in charge. He is quite arrogant and rude. Certainly not what should be customer facing for a luxury brand. I have been in customer service for 38 years, so I understand that some customer’s expectations are not reasonable, or achievable. My request was not unreasonable, and it aligns with the treatment I am accustomed to at Audi, Infiniti, Acura and EVEN GMC. 

I called for a REPEAT visit for a known sunscreen issue with Genesis GV80’s. The issue had ALREADY been deemed a warranty issue the first time my vehicle was in for repairs. The first time I used it, weeks later, it did the very same thing. Since this appointment request was for a repeat warranty issue, and the warranty center is almost an hour away, I requested a loaner. Please note: Every brand dealership mentioned above has provided us with a loaner in situations like this— without an issue. Audi even provided a loaner when I had routine maintenance done, without me even having to ask. The service manager denied my request for a loaner, “unless it was deemed a warranty issue”. I explained the difficulties of not having a vehicle to drive (for the 2nd time), driving over 45 minutes each way, the difficulty of coordinating someone to drive that distance to pick me up and drop me off TWICE……or I am forced to miss work and wait around until the dealership looked at the vehicle and deemed it a warranty issue.  Here’s the REAL PROBLEM. This dealership doesn’t have loaners unless you schedule an appointment 6 weeks out. So, if I drop off my vehicle and they decide it’s a warranty issue they won’t have a loaner available, because it wasn’t scheduled ahead of time. I found that out the first time at this dealership. What would happen then? I would be stuck there.

I also explained that I couldn’t miss work sitting, waiting for a decision. I tried to remind him that it was deemed a warranty issue the first time—and a known issue. He insisted something must be stuck in the sunroof. I told him if something was stuck, then it should have been found the first time the vehicle was in for repairs.  He repeated that a loaner wouldn’t be provided until the vehicle was looked at. I asked if I could have a loaner and they just charge me for it in the event they deem it not a warranty issue. He very rudely said “NO!”. At that point I just hung up the phone as there’s no reasoning with that level of arrogance, and lack of customer service. 

Interestingly enough, 2 weeks later a man claiming to be the dealership’s part-time finance manager pulled into my driveway. He said he saw my Genesis while driving through our neighborhood and stopped to ask if I liked it. I told him I did, but explained the problem and my recent frustrating experience with the dealership. He was very apologetic upon hearing how I was treated, but honestly didn’t seem surprised. 

With that dealership as my only option for an ongoing, unrepaired warranty issue, my husband and I are considering switching back to an Audi. If other customers experience the same attitude when seeking service, they WILL choose other brands when it’s time to replace their vehicles. There should be another option for service/warranty work closer than Alexandria.

column14:
Genesis has customer service level of a Kia. The problem is the program itself, NOT the customer service reps. They’re all courteous and more than willing to help. But they have no power to do anything.

1) the new car buying and delivery experience is no way near to what Genesis made people believed. Not enough inventory, neither custom order. 
2) pick up and drop off maintenance service is a joke. Not only  Genesis Kirkland in Seattle wouldn’t do that. They won’t guarantee me a courtesy car if I drop off my car at the dealership. 
3) all the dealerships nearby have no service schedule available for next 2 months. What a joke. 
4) roadside emergency service, no help at all until about an hour after. By then we have find help ourselves and made it to our hotel. 

I’m very disappointed

When I got home I called Genesis Customer Care, asking if one of the local Hyundai or Kia dealerships that *do* service and sell EVs (Ionic 5, EV6) might be able to help.  Delores told me that wasn't an option, my only option is to drive 200 miles. While I understand, I'm not very happy about it since this is a safety recall (not optional!) and I have to take an entire day or more to deal with this at some point in the future when I have the time.

column14: Case #21820775  Andrew did a great job, this situation does not reflect on him. My situation started in May at Glenbrook of Ft. Wayne. Got the safety recall and about the same time my check engine light came on. Got my appointment with them, they did the safety recall and diagnosed the issue. PO 203 present for cylinder 2 misfire. Upon inspection found fuel leaking from cylinder 2 injector, parts ordered for replacement. Appointment set there, called to make sure parts were in, was told yes. Went to set appointment, was given a loaner, returned 3-4 hours later to find out not all parts were in, was called once parts were in, appointment set. Five days prior to my appointment, was called and told they no longer are a Genesis dealer and can not fix the problem, was told Genesis customer care would be in contact with me. Waited 2 weeks, no call. I made a call to the care line and was set up with Taylor of Perrysburg. I called and explained my issue, they got me in the next day. Upon arrival I was told that there wasn't a service tech available and that whoever I spoke with shoud not of set my appointment. They did set another appointment for next week. But so far I've had to drive 108 miles round trip to Ft. Wayne and 210 miles to Perrysburg with no results. Plus, it's going to take at least 2 trips to resolve my issue. Just having my 2022 G80 a year, is this the level of customer service I can expect ?

column14: I have had the car for a year. The Cherry Hill Genesis dealer I originally contacted, told me 3 months later that they didn't know if they would ever be able to get the GV70 that I wanted and I should look elsewhere. I found the car about 3 hours away, drove up and bought it.  I was told that I could use Cherry Hill Genesis to service the car. It has not been easy. It is about an hour away and the service department is rarely available, I leave a message and don't get a call back. They never have loaner car appointments in a reasonable time period.  Currently, I have a warning alert coming up on the dashboard. The Representative didn't know anything about the issue. He recommended I call for service. I called service on Friday and left a message - no return call. I called on Saturday and was told service isn't there on weekends.  I was afraid to drive my car  this weekend. I bought the top of the line car from a luxury company and was told to expect top of the line service.  This has not been my experience!

column14: Andrew was very friendly and helpful.  However, I am extremely frustrated by the distance I have to drive from my home in SW Virginia to find an authorized Genesis dealer.  I lived in Florida when I bought my car, and I am very happy with the car -- but I would never have bought it if I had known about the shortage of service locations in this area I have moved to.  When I had my car serviced earlier this week at Capitol Hyundai in Greensboro, NC, I was able only to have my oil changed and a general check of the car, but they were unable to correct the problem about which I got a recall notice or to update my navigation system.   A few months ago when I went there for service, Capitol Hyundai was an authorized Genesis dealer, and it was only after I drove two hours from my home to Greensboro that I learned they had lost their Genesis affiliation.  No one told me that when I called to make a service appointment or when I got a text reminder of my appointment a day in advance.   Andrew has sent me information to update the navigation maps on my own, but I have not yet attempted to do that.  His customer care was excellent, but I cannot say as much for Genesis customer care in general.

column14:
Basically it was below average. 
First, the texting service from Clay Nedal was Non-existent.  After 3 attempts of my sending him text, of His Initiating, he never replied to any of them. 
My concern was that when I brought my car in at the designated appointment time, which was set almost 3 weeks in advance, that the correct parts would be in stock.
When I made the appointment with Clay I Specifically asked when I brought my 2024 GV80 in would he have the parts on hand available for install. He told me that they would. 
From that time up the date and time of my appointment I tried calling and texting him 6 times asking him to confirm that the parts would be available when I arrived. I never heard back from him. My Appointment was set for 10am Wednesday,  August 30th. I live 50 miles from the dealership. So, at 7:30 am I called the parts department and spoke with the parts saleman who confirmed that only half of the needed parts were available. He even checked with Clay to see if he may have pull them for my installation,  but he had not. So I immediately called Clay, and was lucky enough to catch him and asked him to cancel the appointment for lack of stock parts.
He did cancel my appointment but also told me that the next available time would be 2 weeks out. I was 1. Very Disappointed with Clay's lack of concern with what I consider "His attention or shall I say Lack Of Attention to my initial request as well as having the audacity to tell me I would have to wait 2 weeks for a slot from my initiating a new appointment request. 
The Install of Mud Guards only takes 1 hr maximum installation time.
The bottom line is I feel like I was treated like I bought a Cheap low end car, Not a Genesis Brand.
I am very happy with the car but the service I got was Hyundai Level, Not what I would expect From The Genesis Brand.
I rate it no more than 2 on a 1 to 10 scale.
P.S. Given my experience I decided to order the parts online from Genesis OEM. When I get them I will call Clay to set another appointment but I WILL NOT EXCEPT HAVING TO WAIT FOR 2 MORE WEEKS.

Sincerely, 
Byron Weaver

column14: It's not often that I input a destination into the navigation systems of our 2023 GV80 or our 2023 G90.   But, when I do, I don't expect to receive this message:  "The route guidance is currently unavailable due to the outdated version of the navigation map.  Please update the map to use the route guidance".   Since updates are supposed to be done over the air, I was at a loss as to why I was receiving this message, why my intervention was required, or how to go about it.  Thus, my call to Genesis Customer Care.   I was informed that there had been TWO updates that our GV80 had not received.  I was given a case number and told that I would receive an email in 2 or 3 days with instructions to update the navigation system.   First, I don't understand why I had to contact Customer Care to initiate a navigation update.  This should have been done automatically.  Second, when I posed the question to the representative, she merely re-read her script indicating I would receive an email in 2 or 3 days.   We are on our 5th Genesis vehicle and currently have two in our garage valued at over $180,000.   If Genesis is going to successfully compete with other luxury brands, this is not the way to go about it.

We have called you all and talked with engineers and sent in photos and still cannot connect. We believe it is software related, but no one can figure it out. Maybe the fact we had a 20 one before? Not sure, but we keep getting the same error code that we need to subscribe to the subscription. However, we are. So now we are at the point where Genesis of Elizabethtown is ordering a new head unit. Although, I don’t think that’s the issue. I don’t know what it is. The Facebook group I am a part of states and possibly is software. I have spent countless hours on the phone and left my car several times at the dealership to see if they can fix this issue. column14:
I love my car, but I have been extremely frustrated in trying to find a dealer in my area who will service my Genesis. It was very unclear as to when the first service for my GV70 2023 Genesis should be scheduled. The message on my car came up at 4,000 miles stating it needed a service. I called three different Hyundai dealers in my area and was appalled at what I found. The Lens Stoler dealership in Owings Mills, Maryland is the closest to me. I called there five times to the service department and no one ever answered the phone and there was no way to leave a message. I called the car sales department there because I knew somebody would answer the phone. Two different people told me they would give my message ( that I wanted to make a service appointment) to the service department and someone would call me. No one ever called me. 
Then I called the Hyundai dealership in Towson, Maryland and was told they do not service Genesis vehicles. I called the Hyundai dealer in Clarksville, Maryland (which is 40 minutes away from me) and was told there was at least a 3-week wait for service. When I inquired about a loaner car, which is supposed to be part of my "perks" for 3 years through Genesis Customer Care, I was told there are no loaner cars and that people are on the waiting list for months to get a loaner when they have a service. The woman I spoke to would not even put my name on the list for a loaner. 
 When I looked online to see what is the recommended mileage for the first service, I saw that 8,000 miles was the recommendation. 
At this point, I was extremely frustrated, so I called the Genesis Customer Care number. Andrew was the representative who answered the phone.  He told me that the first covered service, through my plan, would not begin until 8,000 miles. So now you can see, not only could I not get an appointment to have my car serviced, I came to find out that my car was not really covered for a service until 8,000 miles. I have close to 5,000 miles on my car. 
Andrew was very patient and listened as I told him what I am writing here. He also explained to me about the coverage for the 3-year program. I did not see that written anywhere and I think that needs to be made clearer to customers. He could not explain to me why the Clarksville dealership didn't have loaner cars. The 3-year Genesis customer care program comes with the promise that somebody will come pick my car up when it is ready for the service, drop off a loaner car and then bring my car back. I can't even imagine how that is ever going to happen. I know, through reputation, that Genesis is a great car, but what I have seen of the service available for this car is beyond horrible. I'm hoping somebody can reach out to me and tell me what in the world is going on; are car dealers required to have a loaner car service for Genesis customer care patrons? Why don't all Hyundai dealerships service Genesis cars? I'm nervous about when my car is due for the first service and where I will end up taking it.
 I have previously owned Acuras for 20 years and I never had a service issue like this. I would call a week or 10 days before I wanted a service, I would drop my car off and I was always given a loaner car. Service is the bread and butter of every dealership and I always bring my car into the dealer for service. I'm loyal to a dealer and I take great care and pride in my car.  I don't understand why I am getting such a run around and it's leaving a very bad taste in my mouth thinking about what dealer I will choose to use when the car is ready for service. I would like somebody to reach out to me and assure me that the service promised to me when I bought my car will be fulfilled.

column14: I have to say, I don’t normally fill out a survey like this, but I feel I need to. This was my very first time using the customer care service, and I had a representative from Genesis with me to help show me how to use my new car, which I purchased. Some of the features weren’t working so we opted to call customer care together from the car, but part of the steps to see if it could be resolved involved turning the car completely off and exiting it. She told us it was policy that she could not call the representative on his cell phone or me on mine, so we had to write down the steps and handle it on our own.  However, those steps didn’t do the trick and now it Hass to be sent to the service center for repair. I am still waiting to hear from someone at Genesis to schedule that as I will need a loaner and it seems there are not many available. I am absolutely loving my car, but it’s disappointing that some of the features don’t work with regards to the voice commands, and that nobody has gotten in touch with me  From the service center to resolve it and also that the customer care phone number would tell us to jot down instructions and that we have to hang up and they can’t help us from there. Certainly not the luxury and high-end customer experience I was sold on upon purchasing the car.

The next day the light came back on, made sure the gas cap was screwed securely and the light is still on.  I didn't bother notifying Genesis Connected Services, since it did me no good the day before.  We are out of town, but once I get back in town, I have to go back to the service center to see if they can figure out what's going on.

On the third try, I finally spoke to a person who wouldn't make an appointment, but at least told me to stop by so they can see what is going on.

column14:
The call center and rep experience was great. The problem I have is Lexington Genesis has a long wait (at times 2 months) before you can bring your car in for service.   This particular time I was not in any rush so my appointment in two weeks was fine. However, if I have an urgent repair I should not have to wait 2 months. I traded an Infiniti in for my GV70 and I could always get an appointment within 1 to 2 days. As a matter of fact when I spoke with my neighbor who has a Toyota, he gets appointments within a day or two. 

If you’re going to sell luxury cars that compete with Lexus, Mercedes, Infiniti etc. you need to inform your dealers they need to provide service like their luxury competitors. 

I like my GV70, however I would not purchase another one unless the service appointment time’s improve.  To be clear this is no reflection on the service writers or service manager. They have been very accommodating every time I have brought my car in for service. 

Please have Claudia Marquez (not sure of the spelling) read this comment and perhaps she can call Lexington Genesis and inform them of the standards Genesis aspire to. 

Thank you and you may call me if you would like to. 
James Raim 312.593.6566

For reference, I can tell you that the mapping was more user-friendly BEFORE the update.  They new update, while it gives me access to roads that have been constructed since my car was new, the roads are not identified in the new version.  So basically, I have a map without labels on it.  It’s basically worthless.  I’ve been using the maps from Android Auto which are far superior.  I new “look” of the updated maps needs to include feedback from customers like me.  1.  In addition to the aforementioned issue with the new map not having street names, 2.  When navigating, the street one is traveling on is displayed along with the next turn and the next street name. (Not on the map, but in the directions “box”.). But the font chosen for the street names is so small as to almost render it useless.  If a software engineer wants to contact me, please feel free to do so and I can explain in greater detail why the update was, in my opinion, a dismal failure.

I called because I'm trying out the new Hotspot feature in both of our 2023 GV70s.  While I appreciate the opportunity, the implementation isn't good and I'm not sure there's a solution for it?  It appears you have to turn the Hotspot on EVERY TIME you start your car.  That's just not very good.  My 2019 Mercedes E450 had a Hotspot feature as well, but when you start the car, the Hotspot is on, without the need to go to Setup > Network Data Connection > Hotspot > Enable

I saw a video about using Hotspot in Hyundai cars and evidently this is by design.  But it's a poor design.  If I'm going to pay for Hotspot service in my car, it should be on immediately.  I could understand turning it off.  But it should be on automatically.

Unfortunately, the Genesis is so high tech that it is too complicated for average people to figure out. We love the car, but we may need to trade it in for another brand without the high tech bugs and not owned by Auto Nation the stories of incompetence at the Savannah and Hilton Head Hyundai/Genesis dealers are legendary. column14: Vani, the service rep, was courteous and I believe we both thought when we hung up that my concerns would be resolved however it turns out they are not.  I called Genesis customer care because my connected services had recently stopped working and it was at particularly bad time when I was counting on it.   This is the second time this has happened since I bought my GV70  in September 2022.  I was also due for an oil change.  Vani helped me reboot the system and scheduled an oil change but as usual, the "Genesis dealership" service department which is really just a Hyundai shop does not have loaners or people to pick up up drop off for months.  At the end of my call with customer care, Vani also told me to ask the Genesis dealership to update the navigation system when I got there saying that is why having problems with connected service.  I thought Vani should have said that to the Genesis service department when scheduling.  I'm now at the service department and they say it will cost me $500 and 3-4 hours for them to update the navigation system. They said Hyundai has had recent problems with their customer service system which Vani didn't mention.  They say it is not covered (when I would have thought it was as I have a 2022 GV70) and said they will explain to me how to handle at home.  This information was not shared by customer care.  Also, Vani mentioned that there is a recall related to the fuel system but there is no process yet to actually get that done yet.  In general, I am disappointed that there really is no dedicated Genesis dealership and service center.  I feel when I bought this "luxury SUV"  that Genesis over promised.   I bought this SUV for the advertised ease of courtesy service, security features and reliability.  I don't feel that has been the case -- Lisa Snow

column14: I recently completed this survey regarding our problematic experience at our closest Genesis Service Center: Hyundai of Hilton Head. In short, not only did were they unable to locate the problem, the next day the car’s navigation system indicated that it required updating and essentially became inoperable. It is conceivable that the timing was coincidental and that the service center did not cause the problem, but I would have thought that updating the navigation system was a standard procedure for required service. Now I am unhappy because after spending hours trying to update (unsuccessfully) the navigation system on line, I called to request the update on a USB drive as advertised. I was sent a link to the third party provider, but when I tried to log-on it would not recognize my email and password, which I had just updated a couple of days before during my first unsuccessful and frustrating Genesis Custome Care experience. When I tried calling again the next day (Sunday) the voice recording said the Center was close on Sunday. The information on your website gives  the Sunday hours Pacific time. We love our GV70, but Genesis needs to do some serious work ironing out it’s service systems.

column14: This concierge service was one of the attractive aspects of purchasing my Genesis over other brands. I have found that scheduling my service appointments have been more in line with purchasing a low end vehicle. The blatantly incorrect information on the concierge service for booking an appointment and valet service created confusion, a week delay in service, impact on my work schedule, and having to have the car serviced on my birthday.  This has interrupted by work schedule, my personal schedule and the schedule of others. The actual service appointment made directly with the dealership was also not a pleasant experience.  The service person could not guarantee a loaner (although one was guaranteed when I made my appointment). No one called to confirm the appointment and I had to call. They didn't document was services I was needing and that I required a valet.  Since they couldn't confirm a loaner and couldn't confirm when my vehicle was going to be returned, I had to cancel my birthday plans since I did not know if I would have a vehicle or when I would.  I also found out the dealer does not repair any damage to the body and now I have to schedule another appointment at a collision center for body shop repair.  Luckily I was given a loaner, because I was informed that my car isn't going to be ready by COB today.... but I had needed my SUV to bring some larger items to an event tomorrow, and now I have no idea how I am going to transport my larger items tomorrow.  Overall this has been a disappointing experience that is affecting my desire to purchase another Genesis, since I have been shopping for another vehicle for our family,.

   I would suggest that you change the order so that "general" is at the top of the settings rather than the bottom where I never seem to think to continue to scroll down.  I ran Global Marketing at two financial services companies and one thing I learned is to never make affluent and intelligent, or (at least people who think they are) people feel stupid.  Every six months this car's time keeping makes me and my wife feel stupid.  Make it easier to change the clock.

column14: Marco is not the problem.  The issue, as I told J.D. Power, is that Genesis doesn't have the dealer network to be viable as an independent brand.  I live in Olympia, WA (state capital).  There are only 3 dealers left in Washington, all 2 hours away, and none at all in Oregon.  Marco couldn't coordinate my repairs with the dealer, only set up the tow, so I called Kirkland first.  Couldn't even look at the car until February.  Vancouver said they were 7 weeks out on tow-ins, but might be able to get to a diagnosis in a couple of weeks.  Only Everett said they should be able to get to it in "a week or two" (and it'll take the better part of a day to get a ride up there when it's fixed and drive it home).  Obtaining the maintenance and warranty service I was told I'd be entitled to has turned out to be a nightmare from the beginning.  I tell people I love the car, but without dealer support,  stay away.  At some point, Hyundai just needs to concede that splitting off Genesis as a separate brand has been a colossal failure, and recombine them.  Yes, there's a Hyundai dealer in Olympia.  And no, they won't have anything to do with a Genesis.

column14: This review is becoming the standard for this "luxury" brand Genesis.  Nothing against Jessyca because I never actually interacted with her.  I sent an email to Genesis for trouble with my car and all I got was the runaround.  My GV80 had a map update that I actually paid for because the OTA wouldn't work...Go figure.  Then the Navigation system started acting weird after install (No red light camera warnings).  I confirmed other cars still make the warnings that mine USED to until the update.  Took the car to the dealership who then told me that I had to contact Genesis.  Guess what!  Genesis told me to contact "AutoEver".  Really?!  This is why you will never be a premium brand.  My BMW dealership doesn't tell me to call someone else who then also tells me to call someone else.  To BMW, I'm the customer that bought a luxury premium brand and they take care of everything for me instead of telling me to do more work that by the way still isn't fixed.  It's pathetic.  I bought two of your cars two years ago and have already gotten rid of one of them.  Not because the product is bad.  It's the BRAND!!!  You can't get anything right as far as customer care/service/exclusivity/etc. is concerned.  I'm beyond fed up with this so-called premium brand.  Where I once told everyone about the tremendous vehicles you make, I now caution everyone who asks NOT to purchase unless they don't mind spending extra money to be treated like you bought a used 1985 Honda Civic from an independent dealer.

column14: I purchased my car two years ago from a dealer near Albany, NY. Last month I was notified that the dealership I bought the car from no longer can sell or service Genesis products. I was given information about a new dealership in Albany which would be taking over the Genesis accounts, including mine. A few days ago I received a letter informing me of a serious issue requiring a recall of my vehicle. I called the new dealership in Albany and was informed that they were aware of the recall but couldn’t do anything until they received the proper parts. Since they were a new dealer they did not have the parts on site yet. I was put on a waiting list and was told it would take “about two weeks”  to hear from them. In the meantime I am left with a car I should not be driving due to safety issues and hoping that this issue will be resolved in a reasonable amount of time. I contacted Customer Care to alert them to this issue in the hope they would monitor the situation. I got the impression that there was little that they could do at this point. My concern is that I purchased a Genesis vehicle in good faith and now am left with a dealer I have never met and is not ready, at this point, to care for a serious safety issue. As I live about 90-100 miles from this new dealer I feel I have right to expect the valet service I was told would be available for the first 3 years and that my car will be properly taken care of. I’m willing to be patient but admit that this situation leaves me leery of dealing with Genesis in the future. This saddens me as I thoroughly enjoy my GV70.

column14: Through no fault of Vanessa's she was unable to resolve my problem.  It seems that there is a conflict between the Hyundai and Genesis connected care systems that prevents a single email address from being registered to two different vehicles.  We own a 2018 G80 and a 2023 Palisade.  The original G80 connected services account was registered under an email address that is obsolete and cannot be accessed.  My current email address is registered as a second driver on the Palisade.  Vanessa informed that she could not change my G80 account's email registration due to a system limitation that prevents the same email address from being connected to 2 different vehicles.  The only solution she could offer was for me to create a new "disposable" email address to connect the G80 to.  This is unacceptable and seems like poor software design.  We bought a second Hyundai/Genesis vehicle because of my satisfaction with the G80.  I am somewhat less satisifed as a result of this issue.

column14:
While I love my car and truly couldn’t imagine driving anything else, the Genesis service dept. (specifically dealing with having the car picked up and dropped off) is an absolute nightmare. Genesis is not located near where i live so in purchasing the car the only reason i did was because they offered the car pickup for services. Otherwise it wouldn’t be worth it to have this car. Too much of an inconvenience to get it there for service. But I’ve come to learn while in theory the pickup service is convenient its actually a nightmare. It’s like pulling teeth to get an appointment to start with. Then once you get the appointment, the day the car is supposed to be picked up is always an adventure. I’ve had an issue every time. This most recent time being the worst. First they didn’t show. Then they didn’t have a car to bring to me. Then they had a car but it had no gas. Then they had a car but it was electric and had no charge. Then the guy bringing the car went to the wrong place (an hour and a half away from me). While the girl in service was pleasant and did her best (it wasn’t her fault) it was a nightmare. The questions on the survey don’t really cover the actual issues. Finally the new manager got involved but by that time the damage was done. I spent half of my work day dealing with the endless logistic issues. The manager did his best to make things right in the end. Even offering a detailing of the car that had to be brought had to me a day later because they were so late picking the car up. 
One would think if it takes months to actually get a pickup svc appointment that at the very least they’d have their ducks in a row once it came time for your appointment and would have both a driver and a car available.

There was no help…it felt like the organization just had to check the box to say it cleared the issues. I am still disappointed. However, i am going to still purchase a new car (GV80)  from you guys even through I won’t expect any significant customer support from the corporate level of Genesis. Kinda weird that someone who  took a risk getting your vehicle as a early adopter, doesn’t get the same benefits as other adopters just because they live in a different zipcode. I suggest you review this procedure or make sure the differing offers  are not accessible by all.

I only completed the score is because they were required. A better option would have been N/A. I don’t believe in providing ratings where there was no action on the question asked. Please don’t beat up on Jessyca because of the way the company designed the customer experience in this cause…the engagement was not customer friendly.

Thanks for asking for my feedback

I drove over 1 1/2 hours to Parks because I had good feelings to initial contact with dealership.  The same distance/time if I went to Jenkins Leesburg.  The reason I bought G80 from JenkinsLeesburg was Parks didn’t have one for test drive whereas Jenkins did.
Now I await for response.
Bill Jenkins

column14:
As a Genesis owner, I am deeply disappointed with the company's warranty policies, serviceability, and reimbursement procedures. My recent experience with Genesis Customer Care has left me feeling frustrated, unsupported, and undervalued as a customer.

Warranty Restrictions:

Genesis' warranty is riddled with restrictions and limitations, making it difficult to get coverage for even basic repairs. The requirement to have maintenance performed at an authorized Genesis retailer is an unreasonable burden for many owners, especially those living in areas without a nearby Genesis dealership. This restriction effectively excludes owners from utilizing independent repair facilities, even if they offer superior service and expertise.

Serviceability Issues:

The lack of Genesis Service Valet availability for non-original owners is a significant inconvenience. This service, which provides pick-up and drop-off for Genesis owners, is only offered to those who purchased the vehicle new. This exclusion demonstrates a lack of consideration for existing Genesis owners who may have purchased their vehicle used or pre-owned and actuality the 1st owner of my car was the dealership itself, total nonsense.

Reimbursement Burden:

The reimbursement process for independent repair services is unnecessarily complex and burdensome. The requirement to submit a multitude of documents, including repair orders, proof of ownership, and proof of payment, creates an unnecessary hurdle for owners seeking reimbursement. Additionally, the lack of guaranteed reimbursement leaves owners at the mercy of Genesis' decision-making process, adding to the overall frustration.

Overall, Genesis' warranty, serviceability, and reimbursement policies fall far short of providing the level of support and convenience that premium car owners deserve. The company's restrictive practices and burdensome procedures leave owners feeling undervalued and unsupported.

I urge Genesis to reconsider its warranty policies and make them more customer-centric. The company should expand its authorized service network, eliminate the exclusion of non-original owners from Genesis Service Valet, and simplify the reimbursement process. By addressing these issues, Genesis can regain the trust and loyalty of its customers.

column14: The G80 has been a nightmare. The SAT Nav failed. 5 weeks later a new head unit was installed. It failed in the dealers parking lot. It was a failed antenna. Six weeks later the new antenna was installed and immediately failed. Turns out the amplifier had failed. Again, this was at the dealer while picking it up. The new amplifier took almost six weeks to arrive. It now works. Oops, the connect software is out of date. Now needed to call and spend one hour and five minutes on the phone walking through VIN number and various serial numbers. At the end of all that, I needed to create an account to ship me a USB so I can update myself. This is absurd. My wife's Lexus does it automatically by satellite. Same for all the BMW and Mercedes cars I have owned. The repeated failures of basic electronics and the endless delays in getting replacement parts is not the hallmark of quality. Shabby is more accurate. This car has spent more time in the shop and waiting for boasts than all my cars in the last 25 years combined. 17 days in the shop and months waiting for a head unit, then an antenna and then an amplifier. Serious quality failure for a brand wanting to compete with the very best. It's pretty and drives well, but repeated electronic failures and long waits for replacement parts tell me that Genesis just doesn't care about the ownership experience. Very shabby. I was about to get an SUV or go electric with Genesis. After nine months of failure I will look elsewhere. I'm also waiting to see just how long it takes to get Genesis connect working. I'm using my totally reliable iPhone to do what my G80 should handle. We'll see when and if. Very disappointed that I believed the promise. Reality has been brutal waste of many days and hours. I doubt I'll hear back. Customer service is as bad as the electronics.

column14: I went to Piazza Hyundai and agreed to buy a new GV80, paid in cash, as we were closing the deal for the brand new car the salesman asked me if i was interested in saving some money and buy "a just like brand new" dealer car, 2023 GV80. I made the big mistake of trusting the salesman that it was just like brand new but after going home with the car I immediately called them because I noticed that the manager or dealer beat the shit out of the car. There were rips in fabric, scratches, indents in carpet, beat up tires, etc.. I wanted to immediately bring it back and swap for the new car I originally wanted. I was told they would fix everything in this car, they kept it for about a week and returned with one repair, they just painted the outside! I basically way over-paid for a beat up used car, I would not have agreed to that bullshit deal of saving a little money by buying the "like new" dealer car. I brought this issue up the chain to Hyundai/Genesis management but my case was  eventually rejected and the idiotic reason was that "it did not meet the requirements to be considered a lemon"! I never mentioned that word so don't know how you came to that conclusion. I simply asked for either 1. a rebate to get the car fixed or 2. swap it for the new car.  I never mentioned the word lemon, my complaint was being misled by salesman and management. Internally the car is fine, but I bought a heavily damaged car, nothing very big but lots of small damages that were hidden. So I do take blame for trusting Hyundai/Genesis management but do not think my request for some refund to get the car fixed was unreasonable. I spent a lot of time talking and writing out my issue only to be told "its not a lemon"! So congrats to the Piazza team for getting that beat up GV80 off their lot for the price of a new car!

column14:
I recently ran over some debris with my G-90.  I went to the Springfield dealership and explained o Alex that I thought I might have damaged my undercarriage.  I asked Alex if he could put my car on a lift and inspect the undercarriage.  Alex had to wait until a lift was free, about 15 minutes, and then we inspected the car.  The splash shield covering the oil drain access hatch was torn and folded back.  Alex said he could get the part and replace it for @$104 plus labor.  That afternoon he called me and said he had the part and it I could bring the car back he would have it installed in a few minutes, along with a few missing bolts holding on her parts of the splash shield.  The total bill was about $145 and I couldn't
have been more pleased.  
This is my second visit to this dealership for service, and my second interaction with Alex.   I was equally pleased with my first visit.  Springfield Genesis will now be my first choice for service on my car.

I've always had outstanding service with Genesis -- my only complaints so far are that the app/website doesn't always reflect the service I received at a dealership outside of my "home" dealership (home = where I purchased the car).  Also, the last time  I tried to schedule service, the app/website did not offer the Valet option that I receive with my car so I had to call.  

My only other issue has been with a question that I had after my last service call--> I had requested that the key in my remote be replaced because it wasn't always working/responding properly.  After service, I had asked the courtesy driver if it had been changed and he did not know.  Then I mentioned it during a phone followup survey and asked again -- no follow up or answer was received.  Thirdly (if that's a word), I listed it in one of these surveys and needless to say, I still haven't received an answer to my question.  

Besides those small issues, I love the car.  I would purchase another Genesis product but I would not purchase another electric vehicle until the infrastructure is available to use the car for long distances (I knew this going in, so that's on me).

column14: This continues to be a problem without resolution.  In November, I used the Genesis Connect Service to make a routine, schedule maintenance service visit. There was no available service appointments for over a month.  The Connect Representative even called the local dealership to confirm that there were no earlier appointments available, but supposedly confirmed a December appointment.  I got an email and text confirmation.  Within the last week, I got a call from the dealership that the scheduled appointment was not available.  When I call to confirm/check, I was told that the next available appointment was in March - - 4 months later.  I asked to be connected with the Service Manager that also confirmed that the Genesis Connect scheduled appointment was not accurate and could not be honored.  He volunteered that this "this has happened before."  I have been able to get an appointment in December, but I will now likely be outside the 36month/36,000 mile warranty.   I was told by Timothy that Genesis has made accommodations in the past on the warranty deadline, but that he didn't have the authority to approve this and that I would have to pay out of pocket and fight to get reimbursed under the warranty.  This is unfair and seems like a known issue - - it should not take 4-5 months to get a service appointment, there shouldn't be any disconnect between scheduling while customers were encouraged to use Genesis Connect to make service appointments, the warranty accommodation should be approved without further delay without the need to hope for an after-the-fact resolution.   Sorry for the lengthy email, but I do find this satisfactory and doesn't provide a strong base to recommend Genesis.  Hopefully, there is a resolution of this.  Please feel free to reach out as needed.

column14: Genesis “service” is a disaster.  I called to set up valet service for an oil change.  The call took 22+ minutes, and did not result in an appointment.  Such appointments can only be made by the single individual at each dealership that is responsible for Genesis, and such individuals never, ever pickup the phone.  When I later heard from one such individual, they said the belt service old only be scheduled for 2 months out.  It’s insulting to claim to offer the service, but have it be so useless (nobody schedules oil changes months in advance).  It’s actually unlawful to claim a customer will receive a service but then make it unavailable for practical purposes.  Jamie took forever to find out that the one Genesis service advisor at each dealership was unavailable.  And she waisted a  lot of my time unctiously thanking me for my pittance and for permission to put me on hold for the 5th time.  Months ago, I had a similarly unsuccessful call trying to get roof rack cross bars for my car; I was told that I was shit out of luck, because they were unavailable.  I called around myself and found. Dealer who could get a pair who charged N extortionate amount to install them.  Then there was the episode soon after purchasing the car when it was in the shop for 6 weeks waiting for a part to fix the faulty electronic anti slip differential.  When it first gave a warning light, e Genesis advisor told me to ignore it, even though I later found out that it was a well-known issue.  I had it tied in later after its failure caused a very dangerous situation.  Then there’s the Apple CarPlay that requires plugging in my phone, but when the phone is plugged in, Spotify sound quality is ruined.  A software upgrade could fix that situation, but it’s not happening.
